the game was awesome at the beginning, but they managed to ruin it:
1. due to a low player count, there were instances of imbalanced lobbies with level 100 players facing off against level 10 players. to address this, they increased the hitbox/rate for lowlevel players and decreased it for highlevel players. despite widespread complaints, no actions have been taken. (i played it on a lowlevel account, and the hit rate is insane....)
2. after a few months since the game's launch, the ingame currency system is already broken. most levelup rewards consist of "cookies", which are almost useless because the best skins require real money. a reward cap was implemented a few weeks ago, limiting players to receive max 2 rewards per day. despite daily forum posts (23 every day), they only recently increased the cap to 3 rewards. however, the majority of rewards are still cookies, and the overall quantity has decreased. this means that players have to invest more time but receive fewer rewards.
3. the patch notes doesn't include everything that was changed into the game.

unfortunately the game is slowly going down... if they would like to refund me, i ll return the game immediately.

pretty fun little online brawler. especially fun when queuing up with a friend or playing locally. main problems as of writing the review: afk players and skill disparity in the community. afaik the developers are trying to update the game to make matchmaking more fair, but chances are if you are a casual player and aren't really into the competitive aspect of the game (especially if solo queuing) you won't have a good time. toxicity levels are manageable, some players will focus you (again, a much bigger problem when playing solo) but voice chat is mostly harmless in my experience. 

regarding microtransactions and skins: if you are putting hours into the game  you won't have to pay a dime for pretty much anything you want. i currently only know about 1 skin pack outright locked behind a paywall. level rewards are generous and skins that cost normal currency are basically free, especially once you hit level 100. paid currency drops in decent amounts from level ups, i never had to buy a skin for money and even managed to gift a fairly expensive skin. the issue may become worse (or better, actually) as more content is introduced and additional levels are added (though i'm not aware of developer plans to add more levels atm) 

all in all, if you like competitive online games that are a bit more random party animals comes recommended. queue times are not long right now and the game is not annoyingly random (though this also kinda depends on the map). skillful players will outmatch luck 90% of the time, i'd say. bugs are basically non existent, which is also a big plus. what little bugs i've encountered have been more fun than annoying.

party animals is a game where you do not party with animals. you viciously attack one another with your fists, tasers, bats, pans, hammers, and other oddities you can find in the battlefield in order to win victoriously. with that being said, i do enjoy this game for what it offers. the game comes packaged with a variety of animals to choose from (with the only downside being that some animals/skins of animals are regionlocked or exclusive to certain events making it unlikely to 100% collect every character there is), a bundle of maps with different modes to fight or cooperate on, and achievements that will keep you invested in the game for the long run. however, this is all offered at the beginning of its a launch. with this, along with a few updates from timetotime, the game can feel a bit stale here and there. there are also times where fighting does feel a bit rng, landing hits that have no impact or brushing punches that result in a knockout that stuns you for too long. i highly recommend playing this game with friends in order to have a better experience competing against others either leisurely or competitively. also otta is the best animal. change my mind.

a fun and laidback multiplayer experience

i feel compelled to share my thoughts on party animals because, despite the mixed feedback it has received, i genuinely believe it's a pretty good game. it's important to note that many of the negative reviews may be related to misconceptions about local play, as the game actually requires an online connection. however, this shouldn't overshadow the fact that party animals offers a decent gaming experience.

the game's core loop revolves around a series of minigames and fight rounds in a team format, with team sizes varying between two and four players based on the random matchmaking system. the standout feature is its ragdoll combat mechanics, which some might dismiss as purely luckbased. however, with practice, it becomes apparent that the game can be highly competitive when facing skilled opponents. while luck does play a minor role, mastering skills like quick weapon pickups, accurate drop kicks, and strategic player tossing depends more on player skill and feedback.

admittedly, the game's progression can feel repetitive over extended play sessions, making it better suited for shorter, more casual gaming sessions. the inclusion of a free battle pass system is a nice touch, and despite the presence of microtransactions, i never felt pressured to make any purchases. most of the items available for purchase are cosmetic, and the game generously provides free players with plenty of skins and items.

like any online multiplayer game, the party animals community can be a mixed bag, with elements of toxicity and competitiveness, but it also has its share of friendly and helpful players. ultimately, i'd recommend party animals to anyone looking for a simple, laidback game where you can goof around without taking things too seriously.

in conclusion, party animals offers a fun and enjoyable gaming experience, especially for those seeking a relaxed multiplayer environment with moments of hilarity and skill. give it a try, and you might be pleasantly surprised by what it has to offer.

party animals is a fun game with creative levels and cute characters you can earn through leveling, including additional costumes that can be earned through achievements or the shop as well. so in that sense, there is a lot of variety in which a player can choose and earn through progression. 

however there is a lot of unexplained bs i find myself experiencing the longer this game exists and i play it. i'm discovering i mostly experience this on a handful of last stand maps which include ichiban, winter is coming, wind tunnel, and gator valley. ichiban seems to suffer from irregular and varied windows in which the player will be instantly knocked out from a punch or item used by another player. not to mention it feels i have significantly less time to jump back up out of the gas than others players do, even dying within a second after losing consciousness regardless if i did before i was thrown down there. winter is coming is one of the most bs levels i've played given it seems i freeze a lot quicker than others players do at the end game while they can get up instantly or roll back without ever freezing at the end way too often to not be noticed. i see this happen on variety of other levels as well mentioned above at times including a handful of team levels. i don't know if that's due to anything in particular but it's becoming more apparent the longer i own this game. 

because of that alone, i find myself playing this game less and less due to the bs luck people get in general. as mentioned, they are able to wake from knockouts, get back onto ledges, or even roll back into play before timeouts on various levels way quicker than i can. i don't want to hear the "lack of skill" and that kinda crap. i've played this game during beta over 20 hours including the version from a couple years ago. it wasn't this bad at the start but you notice it more obviously the longer you play, whether a session or playing the game for a number of weeks. i'm seeing a game become less fair in non team games the longer i play this game. sadly that means it's becoming a crappier product unless it's 4v4 a lot of the time to balance out the unexplained bs.

would i recommend the games? yes. however i can't say i tend to have much fun outside of 4v4s with a friend as randoms are insufferable to deal with as your team mates in a 2v2 setting or the fact they expect you to fully carry them.

this game is getting a ton of hate over the gacha mechanics and because there are micro transactions. for one, you do not need to spend any real life money to acquire any skins in the game whatsoever. the ingame currency is attainable through just leveling up and playing the game. there has only been one skin that was locked behind a paywall, which was because it was a collaboration with some other company. i have played for 50 hours now, and have only spent 5 bucks for that one skin, but i have gathered dozens of other customization's through just playing the game. i find it ridiculous how people like to bash this game for it's micro transactions when nobody is forced to pay for it, if they had just played the game they would've had their desired skin in like an hour. also keep in mind this game is $30 dollars, there are companies that actually make you pay $70 dollars and still expect you to pay for a battle pass and other skins, while this game offers everything for free. 

a real critique that i can offer about the game is that it's maps sort of pale in comparison to gang beast's and that maps that are mainly fighting and throwing each other aren't the main focus, but rather more sort these little mini games and team competitions. another critique i'd give this game is that there isn't much else to do after hitting the max level, i personally haven't hit the max level as of yet, however i do hear about there being a lack of content after reaching level 100. the biggest thing that probably bothers me about this game is that there are some skins locked behind doing stuff on other apps, for example there was a tpain skin that you could only get from i believe tuning into the guy's stream. no offense but i aint tryna watch his ahh. there was also a tiktok skin, and other's, that seems like such a chore to do for a skin. 

what this game does well is just laughing at every game. in a typical game you can just expect to be beaten and tossed around, watch a bunny beat a gorilla to death in some corner, and a bear dropkicking some other animal. this game's funky physics, movement, and implementation of weapons and stage hazards, offer a good balance of competition and party craziness. also as i said, the fact that everything is attainable through just playing the game is a big plus, the closest thing i can compare it to is when you would buy a skin pack in pvz garden warfare 2 if that makes sense. 

the one thing that this game will always have my support over gang beasts is that it actually updates there game regularly with new cosmetics and even stages, unlike that dead game that hasn't been updated in over a year. but yeah, this game is fun, definitely needs work on there being grounded stages for just fighting and for there to be a bit more diversity other than just 2v2v2v2, but it's still young and has been making efforts to improve.

[h2] coming from a guy who has seen and played this game for a while, i can tell you the real deal about this game and some confusion people have [/h2]
 
this game is [b] not pay to win [/b] the only microtransactions for the game are cosmetic wise and you can still get the currency from playing the game itself.

[h1] offline misinterpretation [/h1]

what the original description meant for this game is that you could play with your friends via coop mode on the same device/room. the game did not mean to say that you could play without any internet.

[h1] delay problems [/h1]

this game has been around since 2019 and has experienced some long delays in it's life. rest assured, [b] if a game is being delayed that means there it is being polished and worked on to become even greater [/b]

[h1] microtransactions [/h1]

as stated earlier, this game is not pay to win but it does have microtransactions. the only thing you can buy in the game are the currency which [b] can be earned via playing the game [/b]

[h1] future [/h1]

(as of writing this review) party animals doesn't have a lot but it has only been around for a couple of weeks. expect a few glitches here and there and some servers needed for other countries, but the game is excellent and doesn't deserve the amount of hate it is getting now. party animals is an addictingly fun arena brawler with incredibly cute and fuzzy animals, each level has its own unique gimmick and each round feel reasonably short & sweet. 

you can que with up to 3 friends for quickmatch where you can vote on 1 of 3 levels to play which can either be the last stand type levels, where all players are divided into teams of 2 for a first to 3 survival where you try to be the last man standing, hope is not lost if you're eliminated as you can throw in various objects into the field which can either save your duo partner from elimination or secure the round for someone else in a very comedic effect. alternatively you can also vote to play any of the 4v4 team maps where you need to work together as a team to score points and win.

if just playing random maps with other players isn't your forte, then you can always host your own customgames where you can play against bots and customize the game rules to your heart's content, if you only want to play privately with friends then this mode is for you. you even have access to play a pair of fight club levels where your teams objective is to pumble and yeet your opponents off the safe areas of maps until the other team runs out of lives.

as far as balance goes some items can feel incredible oppressive and difficult to work against, unless you can time your punches and jump kicks right you might end up having someone smack you with a shovel until you're knocked out for good or comically yeeted off the stage, while other items like the freeze and stunguns can feel incredibly oppressive to fight against at times, if nobody who's already eliminated knocks down the gun standing player that has someone in an indefinite stunlock, it can very easily feel like you're not allowed to play the game when someone is perfectly positioned to constantly hit you with the stungun with every shot...

if you enjoy fun and over the top comedic brawling games like gangbeasts then consider giving this game a try as well, and if you're a bit picky about your spending then i highly recomend picking this game up when its on a sale.

[h1] 8/10 [/h1] [h1] great game with endless hours of fun [/h1] 
[h2] but... [/h2] [h3] i can already hear the incoming critiques [/h3]

since this is recreate game's [b] first [/b] game we should cut them some slack. giving them feedback is way better than just attacking the developers. they are listening to suggestions and feedback on discord so you should be happy they are doing this unlike other companies who completely ignore the community. you can check their official pages for more info and get updates.

this game is [b] amazing! [/b] i've waited over [b] three years [/b] for it to come out and it's just fun as i remembered. although i think they could have released it back then and slowly added updates to it, i know there won't be the same amount of hype for it as before. hours will fly by and each game does not feel long at all! each game is different and you will always find some crazy way to win or lose. this is why i rate it a 8/10.

[b] now for the bad. [/b]

[h3] weapons: [/h3] something that i've noticed many people comment on, is the balancing of the weapons. 
some weapons are too strong or too random and this factor only frustrates players like myself. if they can make it a set amount of damage per weapon so it can be a skill issue then it will be a blessing, but i doubt this will happen anytime soon. any weapon should not be able to throw you so far! one hit with any weapon it could be a game over for that match.

[h3] grabbing: [/h3] this might sound stupid but why am i able to grab on to well, anything! i know this was intentional as i heard in the tutorial you can grab, pick up, and punch anything. but why! i find myself constantly grabbing on the floor, team members, and that [b] random brick [/b] on [b] "ichiban" [/b]. they should have a feature that only allows you to grab on to certain parts of the map never the floor, as well as not being able to grab and knock out your teammates even though in certain cases you need too for them to survive. i think the game will do just fine and it will get rid of those annoying cases where either you or your teammate ruin the match because one knocks the other out.

[h3] maps: [/h3] some maps need balancing and minor tweaks. for example, i can already tell "beast hockey" will have the lowest play count. it's not because it isn't fun but it's because the puck, and how heavy it is, makes it so unpredictable, anything can happen. you can't run around it on time. you can't stand in front of it or you get knocked and thrown with it. you can hardly move because it's ice...(why not on ice skates and make it faster/better control). you also can't aim properly because of the huge size. i've seen 4 players leave the map all at once and then our team got kicked because there were not enough players. i can hardly imagine how other matches are going. so balancing and minor changes to some maps will make them fun and people will want to play them.


[h3] conclusion: [/h3] there are more things people are rightfully complaining about but it's not a part of the core gameplay. offline, servers, loot eggs, demo rewards, item shop, all can be forgotten when you just want to play the game. well except for offline but you can't expect a 1v1 or a 2v6 (ai) match to be as much fun as the 2v6 (real players) which the maps were intended for. that was an error on their part and if you bought it for offline play then just get a refund. i promise you'll keep the game and it will be much more fun playing online.

hi there,

our intention with th sentence "paw it out with your friends both online and offline." was to convey that you can play with your friends remotely (online), or together in the same location using the same device (offline) through split-screen.

we sincerely apologize for any confusion our wording caused. it was never our intention to mislead our player base about the availability of an offline mode.

the game did not feature an offline mode in the recent three rounds of playtesting either. intentionally misleading our players while conducting playtests that clearly reveal the absence of an offline mode would be nonsensical. review:
buyers beware 

if you get banned, even temporarily, for whatever reason, you will not be able to access the game, not even to play with bots. 

that's what you get with an "always online" party game.




it's a fun game. it can be addictive at times, especially if you don't want to bother playing other games. 

however, the controls are not that good. the hits don't register properly, everyone is flopping around.

there is no way to recover after being knocked down, regardless of your stamina bar. you can mash all the buttons on your keyboard, but it really depends. it becomes frustrating to deal with these mechanics at some point.

some of the maps are also too small and badly designed (gator valley, typhoon). quick deaths are happening, without there being a very clear reason why, especially on maps with various elements (ichiban, ice breaker). two players fall down, at the same time, but somehow one freezes, or drowns or gets poisoned faster. last remaining players all die, but there is no draw, one player manages to win in some way.

the camera is not properly angled, and you cannot really change it.

the force quit punish is nonsensical.

two player splitscreen looks terrible.

the worst of it all, a gacha type system in a children's game, on top of all the microtransactions. it's awful. 


on the plus side, it's a cute game that's best played with friends!
